          "body": "The chapter opens with a case that has no individual perpetrator — an unidentified corpse in the open field. The murder is real; the guilt is real; but no one can be brought to justice. Ancient legal systems often left such cases unresolved. Deuteronomy 21 insists they cannot be. The nearest city bears moral proximity to the unsolved death, and its elders must perform a carefully calibrated rite: an unworked heifer, an uncultivated valley, a broken neck, washed hands, and a covenantal declaration of non-complicity. The priests come near as witnesses and adjudicators (v. 5). The elders pray for atonement in the name of the God who redeemed Israel (v. 8). The bloodguilt is then forgiven — divine passive, God's own act. The rite does not replace justice; it acknowledges that when justice is humanly impossible, atonement must still be sought. The theological logic anticipates Hebrews 9:22: without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness. Even here, in a non-sacrificial rite, blood is the medium through which guilt is resolved."
