          "body": "The captive-woman law is among the most discussed and most misunderstood passages in Deuteronomy. It does not endorse the practice it regulates; it limits what ancient custom treated as unlimited. In the ancient Near East, a conquered woman was property. Deuteronomy 21 does three things without parallel in any contemporary legal code: it mandates a month-long mourning period that honors the woman's grief over her lost family (v. 13); it grants her full wife-status rather than slave-status (v. 13); and it prohibits her sale and commands her release if the marriage fails (v. 14). The law operates within the moral limits of its era while pressing those limits consistently toward dignity. Christopher Wright (*Deuteronomy*, NIBCOT) notes that the law's trajectory is protective, not permissive — it is Moses regulating what Jesus later says Moses permitted 'because of your hardness of heart' (Matthew 19:8). The New Testament does not return to Deuteronomy 21:10-14 as a model but to the creational ideal behind it."
