        "excerpt": "But he shall acknowledge the firstborn, the son of the unloved, by giving him a double portion of all that he has, for he is the beginning of his strength; to him belongs the right of the firstborn.",
        "body": "The inheritance law of verses 15-17 is brief but operates against a well-documented biblical background: the repeated pattern in Genesis in which a younger son displaces an older one (Isaac over Ishmael, Jacob over Esau, Ephraim over Manasseh, Joseph over Reuben). In each Genesis case, the displacement is divinely ordained — God sovereignly chooses the non-firstborn. Deuteronomy 21 is not legislating against divine election; it is legislating against human manipulation. The distinction matters: when God reverses the birth-order, that is His prerogative. When a man does it because he loves one wife more than another, that is exploitation of the legal system.\n\nThe word for 'unloved' (sane) sits at the law's theological center. It is the word Leah bore in Genesis 29:31-33, the word Rachel bore in Leah's mouth, the same term Paul quotes in Romans 9:13 ('Jacob I loved, but Esau I hated') from Malachi 1:2-3. The range of sane runs from active hatred through emotional indifference to relational disadvantage. The law does not require the father to love the unloved wife; it requires him to honor the covenantal reality that her son's birth creates. Sentiment does not override law. The firstborn is called 'the beginning of his father's strength' (reshit on) — the firstfruits of the father's reproductive power, which carries irreversible priority.\n\nThe double portion (shenayim, literally 'two mouths' — a double share of whatever the estate holds) is not an arbitrary custom but a covenantally grounded provision: the firstborn takes up the responsibility of the household, and the additional portion funds that responsibility. The law is thus both protective (protecting the firstborn from his father's emotional preference for another son) and structural (maintaining the social order of the household through objective legal categories that cannot be overwritten by love or unlove).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Bekhor* (firstborn, vv. 15-17) and *bekhorah* (birthright, v.17) share the same root — bkr, the status of first-opening. *Mishpat habekhorah* ('the right of the firstborn,' v.17) is a technical legal term for the entire complex of privileges and responsibilities attending primogeniture — not merely the double share but the familial and covenantal standing that comes with it."
